habitat_description: Petranka (1998) describes adult habitat: "This species is found primarily in deciduous or mixed decduous-conifer forests and is often locally abundant in areas with sandy or loamy soils (Downs 1989)." Breeding habitat usually consists of fish-free ponds, lakeshore pools, marshes, ditches, and ephmeral woodland pools (Petranka 1998). In the southern portion of their range (New England and New Jersey) this species is generally associated with lowland swamps and marshes and surrounding uplands and occasionally overgrown pastures with sandy/loamy soils (Nyman et al. 1988, Klemens 1993). The blue-spotted salamander will migrate several hundred meters between breeding pools and its summer range (NatureServe 2015).
